  "text": "The Rust compiler and Servo browser engine share code through multiple interconnected crates managed via the Servo Stylo project. In servo/servo, the root Cargo.toml (lines 160, 178-183) imports the selectors and style (as stylo) crates from https://github.com/servo/stylo repository. These include: selectors, servo_arc, stylo, stylo_atoms, stylo_config, stylo_dom, stylo_malloc_size_of, and stylo_traits crates. The main style system test entry point is tests/unit/style/lib.rs, which uses selectors, servo_arc, stylo, stylo_atoms, and stylo_traits. The layout component (components/layout/Cargo.toml, components/layout/lib.rs) directly depends on and uses these style crates, importing style::logical_geometry::WritingMode and style::properties::ComputedValues. The script bindings component (components/script_bindings/build.rs, line 18) references DEP_SERVO_STYLE_CRATE_OUT_DIR environment variable, indicating integration with the Rust build system. In rust-lang/rust, the proc_macro bridge is defined in library/proc_macro/src/bridge/mod.rs, which establishes the RPC API interface that Servo build scripts use for procedural macro communication. The proc_macro crate (library/proc_macro/src/lib.rs) exports this bridge module. Servo is also referenced in rust-lang/rust (library/std/src/sys/sync/thread_parking/windows7.rs, line 42) as one of the major projects using the parking_lot crate. The external stylo repository defines the directory structure: selectors/, servo_arc/, style/ (main style crate), stylo_atoms/, stylo_config/, stylo_dom/, malloc_size_of/, and style_traits/. These crates enable Servo to leverage Firefox's CSS styling engine while the proc_macro bridge allows Servo's build scripts to generate WebIDL bindings from CSS properties defined in the style system (as shown in components/script_bindings/build.rs which processes css-properties.json from the style output directory)."
}

